Something I came across yesterday while reading 'serious' stuff. As for first sentences of novels (this one, apparently, belongs to the species) it could enter any competition with a good chance of winning ...

"The past is a foreign country: they do things differently there."

('The Go-Between' by Leslie Poles Hartley, 1953)

Another one on my list. 

Good morning! to all of you.

Believe it or not: Last night I met Nicole Kidman (of all people) in my dream, and though I should have flattered her I said I was thinking about not watching one of the new films she is starring in: 'The Golden Compass'. It is based on the first book of Philip Pullman's 'His Dark Materials' trilogy  'Northern Lights' (at least, this was the title of the English edition). Anyway, yesterday evening I watched the trailer for said movie for the first time, and everything, from the heroine, Lyra, to the landscapes, the architecture, the atmosphere, the feel, absolutely everything collided with the pictures I had formed of the story in my head when I was reading the book. Avoid! I told myself, even though I had planned on going to the movies as soon as 'The Golden Compass' was released. I do not want these film pictures to replace any of those 'paper based' ones I have got in my head. On the other hand, I am strangely fascinated with what other people have made of or, rather, done to the story. I wonder about the author, too. Probably the world in his head looks very different from the one in mine, or in any other's mental universe. Which leads me back to the old question of multiple imaginations springing from one and the same text, and to what I am doing every day, more or less successfully. Do literary studies actually make sense when you realise that there simply is no fixed meaning, and that by reducing the text to structures, certain elements etc., you destroy its wholeness, its completeness, and, actually,  its openness: in short everything that makes it attractive to readers. Even reader response studies based on cognitive theories do this, and be it just because we cannot reproduce the entity of pictures, smells, feelings we have when reading a text, because the moment we do it becomes part of us, and we react to it with everything that makes us individual beings (or not). I wonder about all those people who are not book readers but film watchers only. Do they ever develop their own mental image of a story? Do they continue imagining after the screen has gone black? I know one does, but it is not the same. In the end, strong books, and the images one derives at by reading them, do survive bad film adaptations. For me this was the case with 'The Neverending Story' by Michael Ende. Even the Harry Potter books left more of an impression (in a good or bad way) than the movies did. Maybe I started the discussion from the wrong point of view by setting film adaptation and book against each other, but that is what seemed appropriate in the first place, and I will leave it there to return to literary studies, be they as vain as I sometimes think or fear they might be. Someone, in the end, has to do it :-).

Edit/PS: Having watched the trailer again there is one thing I know for certain: Those magic elements of the story which can only be made visible through computer animation are far too slow, plump and lacking in flow to make them equal to what your imagination can do. This, I am afraid, is part of the problem, and one more reason to keep reading. The pleasure is insurmountable, and far more your own than watching a film could possibly be, I think. I guess I am just stating the obvious here, right? Never mind.

Someone gave me a lovely cup (with a little saucer!) and gorgeous coffee to go with it! Can anyone imagine how pleased I am? 

(I won't mention the sweet little handmade (far-travelled) book that I found in my pigeon hole. Speechlessness says everything, I guess.)

Alles Gute zum Nikolaustag!

mis

What philosophy do you follow? (v1.03)
created with QuizFarm.com

The Cultivation of Christmas Trees

There are several attitudes towards Christmas, 
Some of which we may disregard:
The social, the torpid, the patently commercial,
The rowdy (the pubs being open till midnight),
And the childish - which is not that of the child
For whom the candle is a star, and the gilded angel
Spreading its wings at the summit of the tree
Is not only a decoration, but an angel.
The child wonders at the Christmas Tree:
Let him continue in the spirit of wonder
At the Feast as an event not accepted as a pretext;
So that the glittering rapture, the amazement
Of the first-remembered Christmas Tree,
So that the surprises, delight in new possessions
(Each one with its peculiar and exciting smell),
The expectation of the goose or turkey
And the expected awe on its appearance,
So that the reverence and the gaiety
May not be forgotten in later experience,
In the bored habituation, the fatigue, the tedium,
The awareness of death, the consciousness of failure,
Or in the piety of the convert
Which may be tainted with a self-conceit
Displeasing to God and disrespectful to the children
(And here I remember also with gratitude
St. Lucy, her carol, and her crown of fire):
So that before the end, the eightieth Christmas
(By 'eightieth' meaning whichever ist the last)
The accumulated memories of annual emotion
May be concentrated into a great joy
Which shall also be a great fear, as on the occasion
When fear came upon every soul:
Because the beginning shall remind us of the end
And the first coming of the second coming.

I tie my Hat - I crease my Shawl -
Life's little duties do - precisely -
As the very least
Were infinite - to me -

I put new Blossoms in the Glass -
And throw the Old - away -
I push a petal from my Gown
That anchored there - I weigh
The time 'twill be till six o'clock -
So much I have to do -
And yet - existence - some way back -
Stopped - struck - my ticking - through -

We cannot put Ourself away
As a completed Man
Or Woman - When the errand's done
We came to Flesh - opon - 
There may be - Miles on Miles of Nought -
Of Action - sicker far -
To simulate - is stinging work -
To cover what we are
From Science - and from Surgery -
Too Telescopic eyes
To bear on us unshaded -
For their - sake - Not for Our's - 

Therefore - we do life's labour - 
Though life's Reward - be done -
With scrupulous exactness -
To hold our Senses - on -

(E. Dickinson)

You could take almost everything away but poetry ... and pictures - how can anyone live without them or something equivalent? I don't know.

One of the sweetest novels ever (thanks to MFC):

E.M. Forster: A Room With A View.

Read and enjoy - my warmest recommendations.

mis

ps: It looks as if I may be lucky and have at least partial funding for the next three years. I try not to be happy until it has been confirmed. Wish me luck!

1. first law of drinking: don't drink! second: if you really have to, don't drink zambucha, and white rum in a cocktail together - it will upset your stomach for days ...

2. punting is more difficult than expected - my honor to those we reverently call the CREW (well, it is inscribed on their shirt's backs). i managed to hurt myself and laugh more than in months before. i didn't fall into the water - i am not a coward and - i PUNTED, yeah!

3. still no idea where to live next term. anyone any ideas?

4. saw someone loosing their purse and wandering away, then stop. thought they might go back, having realised that they lost it. another person came, picked the purse up and put it quickly into her shopping bag without looking - all that about one metre from where the owner was loitering around apparently without reason. the finder passed me, silencing her male companion who urged her to 'have a look' - 'not on the street'. - in the forground: the one who found, running away, in the background: the one who lost, not knowing yet, on the verge of a fuss. well - why am i such a coward, that i can see but do not dare to speak? more important: why is honesty so underrated?

5. there are rules which govern the allocation of funding. i hope i will not lose the AHRB's money after having gained an award. still don't believe it.

6. there are scots and scots - according to my experience, the male ones are nice, the female ones - well, take your pick!

8. i did not forget 7, i simply don't like it.

9. a must for cinema enthusiasts current and future: woody allen's 'anything else', to be seen in english, at least twice.

10. 'on the road', interesting but odd - a movie about alcoholism and unemployment, one may think. british.

11. the national gallery is gorgeous, until you come to the point where you want to buy a postcard, and realise that walter b. was a moron in implying the reproduction could destroy the original's aura. oh -mein gott- walter! (shaking my head)

12. and then there is jack gibbons playing gershwin's improvisations on the piano. another reproduction, this time of sounds. odd, but it makes your brain, your heart and your feet beat - 'i got rhythm' that night, i really did!

13. all from me today - not in chronological order, there is al again in ireland, and i still do not know what to feel.

adieu, adieu - remember me. (says the ghost in hamlet, a very good version of which you may see in stratford at the moment, as i. and d. may confirm)

mis

i am back (says the king returning) to the country of translation. research proposals are fun, really. (i'm kidding, of course.) at last - and least - i have a good feeling regarding my topic but do not trust people to give me money for it. the world is poor of mind and pocket (except some), well, there it is, then ;-)

watched 'king arthur' and 'the stepford wives'. the battle on the ice was literally blood-freezing, gripping in the best sense of mindless entertainment. till schweiger, the saxon (hihi)- no comment. (interestingly though, nobody online seems to be sure whether his name is spelt with ei or ai). the worst of all - this film ends like 'robin hood', i wished lancelot had survived and arthur died - (sorry, gwynnie). may the legend live long and prosperously!

the best and by far the most interesting (and well acted) part of the 'wives' was to be seen before the movie actually started. i am referring to the tv-ads from the 60s and 70s used in the opening credits, those housewives and their shining ovens make me want to spit; and then you turn on the tv (i can't though, since i don't have one, thank god) - and there is another smiling face ('i know your paintings well enough' - oh yes sir, do you also know who transformed us into robots?) - praising a new washing detergent, brrr - does anyone want to be kicked, or, want to join me in kicking?

ok, that's enough procrastination for now. my excuses to all movie-enthusiasts, i prefer to be sceptical and cynical, if at all possible.

'That artist or scholar or student in any discipline who is accustomed to comparing himself not with other people working in the same area but with the pursuit itself, the more outstanding he is, the lower the idea he will have of himself. This is because the greater understanding he has of the profundity of that art, the more inferior he will find himslef by comparison. So it is that almost all great men are modest, because they continually compare themselves not with others, but with that idea of perfection which they have in their minds, infinitely clearer and greater than that which the common herd has, and so they see how far they are from achieving it. The common herd, on the contrary, and perhaps at times with truth, can easily believe that they have, not only achieved, but surpassed that idea of perfection which they have in their minds.'

(From: Giacomo Leopardi, Thoughts)

Tell me, by all the melting joys of Love,
By the warm Transports and entrancing Languours,
By the soft Fawnings of the wafting Sheets,
By the dear Tremblings of the Bed of Bliss;
By all these tender Adjurations tell me,
- Am I not fit to write a Tragedy?

(Alexander Pope, Lines on Writing a Tragedy (1711); from: Fragments from Private Letters)
